sing on incorporating big numbers on the left, high-contrast typography for the main title, detailed subtitles and descriptions, core technologies, and styled impact metrics.\n\n\n**Determining the Stacking Mechanism**\n\nI\'m deep-diving into the mechanics of sticky card stacking, inspired by `itboomi.com`. The goal is a clean, overlapping effect. I\'m exploring sticky positioning and z-index to manage the stacking, aiming for a visual cascade where each card slightly overlaps the one below. I\'m thinking of setting the `top` values and z-indexes for a layered effect, ensuring a smooth, professional presentation. I am looking at a scaling method.\n\n\n**Implementing the Sticky Stacking**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the stacking mechanism. I can see how `itboomi.com` uses simple CSS sticky positioning to create an overlapping effect. This approach seems robust and performant. I am looking at applying similar `top` values to achieve a clean cascade; for instance, a slight offset to determine the amount of overlap. I\'m focusing on building a beautiful interface.\n\n\n**Integrating the Card Experience**\n\nI\'m now determining the best location for the sticky card implementation. My thoughts are leaning toward integrating the cards within `ProjectShowcase.tsx`. This aligns with the requirement to replace or augment the existing project presentations. I\'m focusing on directly mapping the project list, including descriptions. I\'m thinking of replacing it with a visual cascade.\n\n\n"
